## Hardware Architecture & Circuit Design

### 1. USB-to-UART Transceiver (FT232RL)
The communications module converts a physical USB interface down to TTL levels for programming the MCU. 
* Cross-coupled hardware serial pins map `TXD` to the MCU `RXD` and `RXD` to the MCU `TXD`.
* A `0.1µF` ceramic capacitor is placed inline with the `DTR` pin to generate the low-going pulse required to toggle the ATmega328P's hardware reset pin during bootloader initialization.

### 2. Power Subsystem
Designed to accept a wide input voltage (typically a 9V battery), the power rail drops down to a stable +5V DC bus.
* **Bulk Decoupling:** Parallel configurations of high-value electrolytic capacitors ($10\mu\text{F}$) absorb massive transient current drops generated during concurrent buzzer and LED deployment. Low-value ceramic capacitors ($0.33\mu\text{F}$) filter high-frequency noise.

### 3. I/O Pin Mapping Matrix

| Component | Component Pin | ATmega328P Pin | Notes |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Crystal Oscillator (Y1)** | Pins 1 & 2 | PB6 / XTAL1 (Pin 7) & PB7 / XTAL2 (Pin 8) | Coupled with twin 22pF caps to GND |
| **I2C OLED Display (U5)** | SCL <br> SDA | PC5 (Pin 28 / A5) <br> PC4 (Pin 27 / A4) | Hardware I2C Serial Bus |
| **Shift Register (U3)** | SER (Data) <br> SRCLK (Clock) <br> RCLK (Latch) | PB3 (Pin 15 / MOSI) <br> PB5 (Pin 17 / SCK) <br> PB4 (Pin 16 / MISO) | Driven via software bit-shifting (`DS`, `SH`, `ST`) |
| **Alarm Output (BZ1 / D7)** | Driver Net | PD5 (Pin 11) | Active-High synchronized output |
| **Reset Interruption (SW1)** | Tactile Button | PC6 (Pin 1 / $\overline{\text{RESET}}$) | Hardware pull-up via $10\text{k}\Omega$ to +5V |

